Features extracted from the comparison of tolerant and non-tolerant patients

St Louis cohort

For the patients from the St Louis cohort, I extract the CyTOF, metabo and transcriptomics features that had the same behaviour in both cohorts:

ft_integ_louis <- readRDS("~/Documents/VIB/Projects/Integrative_Paris/Integrative/outputs/data/integ/cyt_met_rna_beh_features.RDS")

I extract the metadata (age, gender, …) for the St Louis cohort

Cryostem cohort

For the patients from the Cryostem cohort, I extract the CyTOF, metabo and transcriptomics features that had the same behaviour in both cohorts:

ft_integ_cryo <- readRDS("~/Documents/VIB/Projects/Integrative_Paris/Integrative/outputs/data/integ_national/cyt_met_rna_beh_features.RDS")

I extract the metadata (age, gender, …) for the Cryostem cohort

## [1] 1
## [1] 1

## 4      M CHU Angers            21.09.2017   primary_tolerant          MM

## 2     16936       11
## 3     12009       00
## 4     22713      0NA
## 5     17236       00
## 6     12793       00

I add the metadata information to my table for later:

recip_info_cryo <- recip_info_cryo %>% 
  mutate(Id.Cryostem.R = CyTOF.Name)

ft_cryo <- left_join(ft_integ_cryo,
                      recip_info_cryo, 
                      by = "Id.Cryostem.R")

Both cohorts

I can now merge St Louis and Cryostem patients into one big table, and perform PCA:

pca <- prcomp(ft_integ_2_cohorts, center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)
plot(pca)

And plot the patients coloured per group:

A large number of the non-tolerant patients are on the right of this PCA. Among these non-tolerant patients, we retrieve the patients that we had already identified as special in the CyTOF data of the St-Louis cohort: R836, R219, R830, R598, R690

ggplot(ft_2, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, col = CMVStatus), label = Id.Cryostem.R) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_text(aes(label=Id.Cryostem.R),hjust=0, vjust=0) +
  scale_color_manual(breaks = c("0", "1", "NA"),
                     values = c("grey", "black", "violet"))
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Many of these patients have CMV. We can see which CyTOF, metabo and transcriptomics features are pushing the patients to the right on the PCA:

Different approach : clustering

We can use a different approach by clustering the patients into 2 clusters based on ther CyTOF, metabo and transcriptomics features.

How were the patients split? In cluster 1, we have more non-tolerant patients, of which a high majority has CMV. In cluster 2, there are mainly tolerant patients, and the CMV is 50/50

cl1 <- rownames(ft_2_km)[which(km$cluster == 1)]
cl2 <- rownames(ft_2_km)[which(km$cluster == 2)]

ft_km <- ft_2 %>% 
  mutate(clustering = km$cluster)
table(ft_km[,c("GROUP", "CMVStatus", "clustering")])
## , , clustering = 1
## 
##               CMVStatus
## GROUP           0  1
##   non_tolerant  4 11
##   tolerant      3  4
## 
## , , clustering = 2
## 
##               CMVStatus
## GROUP           0  1
##   non_tolerant  3  5
##   tolerant     14 15

Which variables differ the most between the two clusters?

I can then merge the two cohorts into one dataset:

if(all(colnames(ft_recip_cyto_louis) == colnames(ft_recip_cyto_cryo))){
  ft_cyto <- rbind(ft_recip_cyto_louis,
                   ft_recip_cyto_cryo)
}

And apply PCA to the data:

pca <- prcomp(ft_cyto, center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)
plot(pca)

We can plot the patients coloured per group:

A large number of the non-tolerant patients are on the top of this PCA. Among these non-tolerant patients, we retrieve the patients that we had already identified as special in the CyTOF data of the St-Louis cohort: R836, R219, R830, R598, R690

ggplot(ft_2_cohorts, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, col = CMVStatus), label = Id.Cryostem.R) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_text(aes(label=Id.Cryostem.R),hjust=0, vjust=0) +
  scale_color_manual(breaks = c("0", "1", "NA"),
                     values = c("grey", "black", "violet"))

Many of these patients have CMV. We can see which CyTOF features are pushing the patients to the top of the PCA:

Different approach : clustering

We can use a different approach by clustering the patients into 2 clusters based on ther CyTOF features.

How were the patients split? The two clusters don’t seem very interesting to us, cluster 1 is only slightly enriched in CMV+ and non tolerant patients.

cl1 <- rownames(ft_2_km)[which(km$cluster == 1)]
cl2 <- rownames(ft_2_km)[which(km$cluster == 2)]

ft_km <- ft_2_cohorts %>% 
  mutate(clustering = km$cluster)
table(ft_km[,c("GROUP", "CMVStatus", "clustering")])
